Experiment: Installing and Running a Linux Virtual Machine

Aim
To install and execute a Linux virtual machine using virtualization software and confirm that it boots correctly.

Objective
Understand the concept of virtualization.

Learn how to import and run an OVA file.

Verify that a Linux virtual machine functions properly.

Theory
About Virtualization
Virtualization is a technique that enables multiple operating systems to run simultaneously on a single physical computer by using software such as Oracle VirtualBox or VMware Workstation. An OVA (Open Virtual Appliance) file contains a pre-built virtual machine, complete with an operating system and predefined configurations. Importing this file into virtualization software allows users to set up a fully functional system quickly, without needing to perform a manual OS installation.

Step‑by‑Step Procedure: Installing Linux Using VMware
Install VMware Workstation on the host machine.

Launch the VMware Workstation application.

Select "Open a Virtual Machine" from the menu.

Browse and select the desired OVA file.

Import and convert the virtual appliance as prompted.

Review the hardware settings (memory, CPU, storage) and adjust if necessary.

Power on the virtual machine.

Log in to the Linux system and verify that it boots successfully without errors.

Results
The virtual machine was imported successfully.

The Linux operating system booted without any errors.

The system responded correctly to all commands entered.

